❯ can we accelerate a single file upload with sending multiple chunks at a time from client (just asking do not implement)

● Yes, but it comes with trade-offs worth understanding:

  What changes client-side
  Instead of for (const ci of missingChunks) sequential, you'd do batches — e.g. 4 concurrent fetch() calls via Promise.all or a semaphore pool.

  What changes server-side
  The current server already supports concurrent chunk uploads correctly — pwrite() at independent offsets, fcntl write-lock only on the bitset,
  and the .data file is preallocated so no seeking races. So the server needs no changes for correctness.

  Where the speedup actually comes from
  - Hides per-chunk round-trip latency (especially useful on high-latency links)
  - Keeps the server busy during the gap between client finishing a chunk read + hash verification and starting the next recv()
  - On a local LAN or loopback this gives near-zero benefit since RTT ≈ 0

  Real risks
  - Memory pressure: with 4 MB chunks and 4 concurrent uploads, the client holds ~16 MB of ArrayBuffers in flight at once (plus the browser's fetch
   buffers). With 16 MB chunks that becomes 64 MB
  - TCP congestion: multiple concurrent streams compete with each other on the same connection pool — you may not get 4× throughput, you may just
  fragment the available bandwidth
  - Out-of-order completion reporting: the progress bar becomes harder to track — chunk 5 can complete before chunk 3, so you can't just increment
  a counter linearly
  - ETA accuracy drops: speed estimate based on wall time becomes noisy when multiple chunks overlap

  Practical recommendation
  Concurrency of 2–4 is usually the sweet spot for WAN uploads. Beyond 4, you hit diminishing returns and the memory cost starts mattering. For a
  LAN NAS (which is what this server is), sequential at 4 MB chunks already saturates a gigabit link — the bottleneck is disk write speed, not
  network latency.


